Yasuke (彌 介, Yasuke), Also known as Kuro san (kuro meaning black) or Kurosuke, is an African slave who lived in the 16th century and became a samurai in Japan.Little is known about his life and the main source for him is The History of Japan written by the Jesuit missionary Luís Fróis.

Other accounts of Japanese and European travelers evoke Yasuke. He is also a recurring character in Japanese folklore.

he fascinates with his large size (Matsudaira Ietada in his diary describes him as measuring 6 shaku and 2 sun or 1.88 m while the average height of a Japanese man at the time is 1.57 m) and by the fact that he quickly masters the Japanese language.

The Japanese had never seen someone with such dark skin before and Nobunaga ordered them to take a bath to verify that it was their natural skin color. He soon harbors great affection for this man and gives him the name Yasuke. The most common nickname given to the African is Kuro san (from kuro, "black": Kuro san can be translated as "Mr. Black"). Nobunaga is impressed by Yasuke's intelligence, language skills and physical strength. He is also fascinated by everything exotic and makes the slave a permanent exhibit at court.

Nobunaga frees him and offers him an official position of samurai. Yasuke then becomes his bodyguard. The daimyo gives him his adopted daughter as his wife and Yasuke becomes court counselor.

In 1582, Nobunaga was defeated in Kyoto by Akechi Mitsuhide's army. Yasuke then sets out to meet his lord's heir at Nijō Castle. Oda Nobutada in turn attacked and defeated, Yasuke is taken prisoner by Akechi Mitsuhide and presented in front of him to decide his fate. It is declared that he is not a man but a beast, that he knows nothing and is not Japanese, but that he should not be killed but handed over to the Jesuits. No one knows what happened to him after this event
